Research the full taxonomy of object-oriented code complexity metrics beyond cyclomatic complexity, focusing on the Chidamber and Kemerer (CK) metric suite and its successors. Cover the following metrics in depth: Weighted Methods per Class (WMC), Coupling Between Object Classes (CBO), Response For a Class (RFC), Lack of Cohesion in Methods (LCOM and LCOM4), Depth of Inheritance Tree (DIT), and Number of Children (NOC). For each metric, document the original formula, the empirical studies that validate or refute its predictive power for defects and maintenance effort, the recommended threshold values from the most-cited studies, and whether modern tools like SonarQube or Understand actually implement it. Also research the more recent extensions: TCC (Tight Class Cohesion), LCC (Loose Class Cohesion), and the MOOD metrics. Include research on which CK metrics have been shown in meta-analyses to have the strongest correlation with post-release defect density, and which have been challenged as unreliable. The practical goal is to identify which of these metrics are worth implementing in a multi-language static analysis tool and what their implementation complexity looks like when working from an AST without a full type system.
